         "id": "SECTION_introdução",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nWriting emerged in Sumeria around <htdate0>, initially in a pictographic manner — that is, through the drawing of symbols that remind us of something, like objects — subsequently moving to a method that reproduces sounds: phonetic writing (<htcite0>). However, the fact that it emerged in Sumeria does not mean that other peoples copied it directly. Different writing systems emerged in other places, completely independently (<htcite1>).\n\nSince writing represents the sounds we produce, logically, they came first, which leads us to our initial reflection.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "73c1fc70-769e-47cb-a7b4-597a73d21a93",
                     "text": "Dr. Irving Finkel",
                     "page": "00:05:20 - 11:40",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2019",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "5390fa3b-735f-4e22-ac98-178303a13fdb",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Writing System",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "-3400",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: Is it necessary?</b><br /><br />Would all the peoples of the planet have created a writing system?<br /><br />Or did some not feel the need to do so and, even so, manage to transmit knowledge?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_voice",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### When did the voice emerge?\n\nSpeech, as we know it, occurs due to morphological differences — variations in the human body compared to other animals — that possibly contributed to, or accompanied, the emergence of speech in our species (<htcite0>).\n\nHowever, despite articulated speech being a human characteristic, the voice is also present in other primates, such as chimpanzees (**Figure 1**), orangutans, and primates in general (<htcite1>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "da4b4f3a-f48c-4c17-87ca-0ebad8ba1165",
                     "text": "Belin, P.",
