      {
         "id": "SECTION_teaching",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Oral Knowledge Transmission\n\nWe, *Homo sapiens*, emerged on Earth at least 300,000 years ago, although other species of the genus Homo emerged around 2,000,000 years ago (<htcite0>; <htcite1>).\n\nSince writing is recent when compared to our speciation process — the process by which new species emerge over generations, accumulating changes — we must assume that, for a long time, knowledge was transmitted through speech.\n\nThe transmission of knowledge and traditions through orality can be observed for centuries among the Shona people of Zimbabwe, through the organization and structure of their kitchens (**Figure 2**) (<htcite2>; <htcite3>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "8b0527b7-cf08-4e3b-8148-347cd178e607",
                     "text": "Tuttle, R.H.",
                     "page": "Human Evolution",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "1",
                        "day": "23"
                     }
